  "text": "<html>\r\n    <head>\r\n    <style>\r\n        .unselectable {\r\n          -webkit-user-select: none;\r\n          -webkit-touch-callout: none;\r\n          -moz-user-select: none;\r\n          -ms-user-select: none;\r\n          user-select: none;\r\n        }\r\n      <\/style>\r\n      <\/head>\r\n\r\n<body class=\"unselectable\">\r\n\r\n    \r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>OXIDATION AND REDUCTION\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">OXIDATION AND REDUCTION<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">In terms of oxygen, the oxidizing agent is usually defined as the oxygen donor while the oxygen acceptor is the reducing agent. So, the oxidized species is the one that gains oxygen from left to right of an equation. In the given equation, the reduced specie (the oxidizing agent) is Pb4+, which loses electron to become Pb3; hence, it is the oxidizing agent.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">Oxidizing agent also means a substance that cause oxidation while a reducing agent is a substance that causes reduction. Oxidation is the addition electronegative atom to a substance. it is also the removal of hydrogen. Reduction is the removal of electronegative atom. it is also the addition of hydrogen to a substance. Loss of electron is oxidation while gain of electron is reduction. Oxidation involve the increase in oxidation number while Reduction involve decrease in oxidation number.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">PbO<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;+ 2HNO<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>3<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;+ H2O<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Wingdings;\">\uf0e0<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;Pb(NO<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>3<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">)<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;+ 2H<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">O + O<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">Pb4+ in PbO<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;was reduced to Pb<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">+ in Pb(NO<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>3<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">)<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">Corrosion reaction<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">A corrosion reaction can be considered as composed of two half-cell reactions. One of the half cell reactions corresponds to &#39;oxidation reaction taking place on the &#39;anode,&#39; and the other half cell reaction corresponds to &#39;reduction reaction&#39; taking place on the &#39;cathode&#39; of the cell.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">Rusting of iron is corrosion of iron. Rusting of iron takes place when iron corrodes in the presence of water and oxygen. It is a redox reaction whereby oxygen acts as an oxidising agent while iron acts as a reducing agent.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">Fe + H<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">O + O<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;<\/span><img src=\"data:image\/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAA0AAAATCAYAAABLN4eXAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABmSURBVDhPY\/hPIvj379+cUU1AMMg0vXnz5r+WlhaUR4JNR48e\/a+mpgZmwzWxsLAQxAwMDP9tbGyIt+nx48f\/RUVF\/3\/\/\/p04TZ8\/f\/6vrKwM5RHppw8fPkBZEEC085DB8NT0bw4AhoGlAUzAsxAAAAAASUVORK5CYII=\" width=\"13\" height=\"19\" alt=\"\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;Fe<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">O<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>3<\/sub><\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">A bleaching agent is a substance that can whiten or decolorize other substances Bleaching agents&rsquo; reaction is by act oxidation or reduction, the chromophores which are a group of atoms responsible for the different colours of coloured substances. The oxidizing bleaching agents are chlorine, chlorine dioxide, alkaline hypochlorites, sunlight, etc. Reducing agents used in bleaches include sulfites, bisulfites, and sodium borohydride.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">White silver chloride decomposes and precipitate takes on a purplish colour when first exposed to light. This darkens and becomes greyer in colour.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">Change in Oxidation number<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">It is solved by substituting the oxidation number of other elements and solving for the oxidation number for both the right and left equation. E.g.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">Cr<\/span><img src=\"data:image\/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABgAAAAVCAYAAABc6S4mAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAHdSURBVEhLvZS9rylBGIdVSiEUJKJUUBCliE5UImoNiValVopKNHQk4iMKlU5x\/wMkEg2hQUIUQiK+P37nzHsne3aPa\/dsce6TzO6877szT3Z2djT4RZ7P5x9Vgs8BOB6PuF6vPCOPKsF8PofVakW1WoXZbMZwOOSV96gSbDYbnE4n6nc6HcTjcerL8SJ4PB5YLBaYTqc4n888+0oul0OpVOLReySC8XiMYDCIRqOBVqsFl8tFy\/Gd0WiEaDTKI3kEweFwgFarxWw2owJjuVxSrt\/v8wyw2+3g8\/l49JdCofDPVi6XvwTFYhF2u50GiPH7\/QgEAjwC3G43brcb9SeTCd3lEAR6vR4ej4eSYpLJJDQaDU3abrdhMpngdDrhcDgQCoX4U+8RBGySVCpFSTHZbJZql8sF2+0W6\/VaaGy5lJAIEokEJcWIBYPBAAaDQdKUkAjYrvlOJBKhGoN9bLZU9\/sdq9XqRztJENTrdVgsFkqK8Xq9yOfzPPoinU7TMikhCNhPpdPpUKlUqMDo9XowGo109ojZ7\/cvW\/UdgoDBJgqHw7RzMpkMYrHYy+QM9kbdbpdH8kgEP4F9bJvNxiNlVAuazSZqtRqPlFEtYOeQGlQL1PJ\/BJ8X7++1p\/MDKaEnso9gSf8AAAAASUVORK5CYII=\" width=\"24\" height=\"21\" alt=\"\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;+ 14H<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>+<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;+ 6I &rarr; 2Cr<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>3+<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;+ 3I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">+ 7H<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">O<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">The change in the oxidation number of oxygen in the equation above is<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">A. 0 B. 1 C. 2 D. 7<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">(2009\/2010 no 9)<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">A&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">0<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">The oxidation number of oxygen on the left hand side. Cr<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">O<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>7&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Wingdings;\">\uf0e0<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">2Cr +7O= -2<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">2(+6) + 7O = -2<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">+12 + 7O = -2&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">7O = -2 -12 = -14&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">O = -14\/7 = -2<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">The oxidation number of oxygen on the right hand side<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">H<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">O&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Wingdings;\">\uf0e0<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;2H + O = 0&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">2(+1) + O = 0&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">+2 + O = 0&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">O = -2&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">The left-hand side = right hand side, change in oxidation number of oxygen in the equation is zero.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">Under the action of light, chlorine water gives oxygen and hydrochloric acid. Chlorine water is a name of a solution of chlorine<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">HOCl&nbsp;<\/span><img src=\"data:image\/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAA0AAAATCAYAAABLN4eXAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABmSURBVDhPY\/hPIvj379+cUU1AMMg0vXnz5r+WlhaUR4JNR48e\/a+mpgZmwzWxsLAQxAwMDP9tbGyIt+nx48f\/RUVF\/3\/\/\/p04TZ8\/f\/6vrKwM5RHppw8fPkBZEEC085DB8NT0bw4AhoGlAUzAsxAAAAAASUVORK5CYII=\" width=\"13\" height=\"19\" alt=\"\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">&nbsp;HCl +&nbsp;<\/span><img src=\"data:image\/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABcAAAAZCAYAAADaILXQAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAGrSURBVEhLvZS9y0FRHMevwcsoymrHYFRKJjKYLcqgZ\/AfPLO\/4Frskl02lDKIlEnyxKJIKUophdwv59wf0nU57vN4PnXqfM\/Lp9PvnnMlfAhFUX7+V348HnE4HCgZ505+Duj1egiFQuh0OjRqnKt8uVwinU4jmUxCkqS\/le\/3e2y3W6zXa2E5W\/cMTc1F5dVqFalUitJjDMv9fj8GgwGlxxiSj0YjBINBSvoYkvf7fUQiEUr6GJKzeRE08tVqxTc3m00auYddWZ\\" width=\"23\" height=\"25\" alt=\"\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri;\">O<\/span><span style=\"font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>2(g)<\/sub><\/span><\/p>\r\n \r\n<\/body>\r\n\r\n<\/html>",
  "chapIndex": "OXIDATION AND REDUCTION"
